While you can observe similarities in the behavior of networks, there is no rigorous mathematical equivalence relation for neural networks. This is because there are an infinite number of ways to build a neural network, a problem that is referred to as the CTQW problem. This gives rise to the question How can we tell if two networks are actually equivalent?
USUAL_ANSWER: There is no mathematical proof of network equivalence. However, one approach is to ensure all networks have the same number of parameters, and then compare their values pairwise per layer through combinatorial search. If this produces two network equivalent to the pattern (all weights in the networks—statically and adaptively—decomposed across multiple layers, all initially close to zero), then you will also be able to generate several patterns performing the same as the original systems \cite{upchurch}. One drawback is that this approach is computationally intensive.
